opriate value.", "\"OBJECTIVES OF TRANSFER PRICING\":\"The objectives of transfer pricing are goal congruence, divisional autonomy, and divisional performance evaluation.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF GOAL CONGRUENCE\":\"EXAMPLE OF GOAL CONGRUENCE\"\n\nABC Consulting, a firm with offices in several major cities, provides an example of goal congruence in transfer pricing. This occurs when consultants in one office make decisions that benefit the entire organization. However, there was an instance where ABC Consulting's internal transfer pricing led to a decision that was advantageous for the Budapest office but not for the overall company, illustrating goal incongruence. This highlights the importance of aligning individual office goals with the broader objectives of the company to achieve overall success.", "\"ROI AND RESIDUAL INCOME CALCULATION\":", "\"DIVISIONAL AUTONOMY\":\"Divisional autonomy refers to the freedom of divisional managers to make their own decisions, which can improve motivation but may lead to imbalanced transfer pricing.\"", "\"SUPPLYING DIVISION PERSPECTIVE\":\"The supplying division will accept a minimum transfer price equal to the marginal (variable) cost plus the opportunity cost.\"", "\"SCENARIO 1 - OPPORTUNITY COST IS ZERO\":\"When there is no external market or there is spare capacity, the opportunity cost is zero, and the minimum transfer price is the marginal cost.\"", "\"QUIZ: NO OPPORTUNITY COST\":\"This quiz involves calculating the minimum transfer price when there is no opportunity cost and determining the actions of divisions in such a scenario.\"", "\"SCENARIO 2 - OPPORTUNITY COST ARISES\":\"An opportunity cost arises when an internal sale sacrifices an external sale, and the supplying division operates at full capacity.\"", "\"QUIZ: WITH OPPORTUNITY COST\":\"This quiz involves determining the minimum transfer price when there is an opportunity cost and evaluating the actions of divisions in such a scenario.\"", "\"MARKET PRICE METHOD\":\"The market price method sets the transfer price based on the external market price. It may need to be adjusted downwards if internal sales incur lower costs than external sales, such as lower delivery costs.\"", "\"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\":The \"FULL COST PLUS METHOD\" sets transfer prices by adding a markup to the full cost of production. This method ensures that the supplying division covers its production costs. However, it may lead to dysfunctional decisions if there is spare capacity. Under this method, the supplying division charges the full absorption cost plus a markup. To avoid transferring inefficiencies from the selling division to the buying division, standard costs should be used rather than actual costs."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}